{"id":"1605.09765","submitter":"Matthias R\\\"oger","authors":"Keith Anguige, Matthias R\\\"oger","title":"Global existence for a bulk/surface model for active-transport-induced\n  polarisation in biological cells","comments":"25 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider a coupled bulk/surface model for advection and diffusion of\ninteracting chemical species in biological cells. Specifically, we consider a\nsignalling protein that can exist in both a cytosolic and a membrane-bound\nstate, along with a variable that gives a coarse-grained description of the\ncytoskeleton. The main focus of our work is on the well-posedness of the model,\nwhereby the coupling at the boundary is the main source of analytical\ndifficulty. A priori $L^p$-estimates, together with classical Schauder theory,\ndeliver global existence of classical solutions for small data on bounded,\nLipschitz domains. For two physically reasonable regularised versions of the\nboundary coupling, we are able to prove global existence of solutions for\narbitrary data. In addition, we prove the existence of a family of steady-state\nsolutions of the main model which are parametrised by the total mass of the\nmembrane-bound signal molecule.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 May 2016 18:55:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-06-01"}
